{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631368"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17366"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17366"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115212"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10056"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17366"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97220"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7839"},{"type":"tags","id":"7845"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23558"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115212"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is conducting a case-control study examining the relationship between childhood infections and the development of autoimmune disease in adults. A survey is provided to cases (people with autoimmune disease) and controls (people without autoimmune disease) which includes collecting information about childhood infections numbers and severity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main type of information bias likely to affect this study?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observer bias","Selection bias","Recall bias","Response bias","Measurement bias"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecall bias\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely type of information bias in this study. People with autoimmune disease (cases) may be more motivated to thoroughly remember and report childhood infections compared to controls, as they search for explanations for their condition. This creates systematic differences in how exposure information is collected between groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelection bias\u003C/strong\u003E relates to systematic differences in how participants are recruited into the study groups, not how information is collected. \u003Cstrong\u003EObserver bias\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when knowledge of participant status influences how researchers collect or measure data. \u003Cstrong\u003EMeasurement bias\u003C/strong\u003E typically refers to systematic errors in the tools or methods used to measure variables. \u003Cstrong\u003EResponse bias\u003C/strong\u003E refers to systematic differences in how participants respond to questions, usually due to social desirability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecall bias is particularly problematic in case-control studies where participants are asked to remember past exposures, as cases often recall exposures differently than controls due to their search for causation of their condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Information bias occurs when there are systematic differences in how data is collected between groups in a study.","Recall bias is a type of information bias where participants with a condition may remember exposures differently than those without.","Observer bias is a type of information bias where knowledge of exposure/outcome status influences how data is collected or measured."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97220"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17366"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97220"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:03:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10056"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115212"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4948"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cr